	<article id="post-4360" class="post-4360 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-features">
				<header class="entry-header">
									<h2>From Homebound to School Bound with Telepresence Robots</h2>
			<h3 class="news_meta">December 19, 2017</h3>
								</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p><em>Informatics Professor Emeritus Judy Olson has teamed up with Ph.D. candidate Veronica Newhart to research telepresence robots for learning.</em></p>
<p><span id="more-4360"></span></p>
<p>When a child is cut off from school because of an illness or disability, he or she can miss out on more than just classroom learning. Disconnected from school friends and unable to participate in extracurricular activities, the child can start to feel isolated. According to Informatics Professor Emeritus <a href="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/explore/faculty-profiles/judy-olson/">Judy Olson</a>, the public school system usually provides four to five hours of teaching a week ‚Äî not day ‚Äî for homebound students. ‚ÄúThe school leaves a box of materials, but who is supposed to monitor the student and do all this stuff? And the children might get depressed and check out.‚Äù</p>
<div id="attachment_4361" style="width: 560px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Festival_of_Discovery.jpg"><img class="wp-image-4361 size-full" src="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Festival_of_Discovery.jpg" alt="" width="550" height="484" srcset="https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Festival_of_Discovery.jpg 550w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Festival_of_Discovery-300x264.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 550px) 100vw, 550px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A demonstration of a telepresence-learning robot at UCI‚Äôs Festival of Discovery.</p></div>
<p>Olson, who has been exploring the use of <a href="http://www.ocregister.com/2013/11/17/robots-let-doctors-beam-into-remote-hospitals/">robots in medicine</a> for years, is now teaming up with <a href="http://education.uci.edu/phd-newhart-v.html">Veronica Newhart</a>, a Ph.D. candidate in the School of Education researching telepresence robots for learning. Although Olson retired in December 2016, she is spending much of her time advising Newhart on informatics-related issues. Together, they‚Äôre collecting stories about children like 11-year-old <a href="https://www.voanews.com/a/robot-takes-recovering-child-seat-class/3828641.html">Cloe Gray</a>, who started using a robot to attend school while recuperating from leg surgery. Yet Newhart and Olson aren‚Äôt just gathering news stories. They‚Äôre tracking a network of telepresence robots for homebound students at schools in three of the largest school districts in the nation and for 15 additional students. In particular, they‚Äôre checking to see how the students are doing and are asking about desired features for the robots.</p>
<p><b>Designing the Experience</b></p>
<p>‚ÄúWe have this wonderful story of this little boy who has a heart condition, and his mother kept saying, ‚ÄòI don‚Äôt think he has the energy to go to school on a robot,‚Äô but they agreed to give it a try,‚Äù says Olson. So, the student received a robot and training, and on the first day, he stayed in classes for six hours. He‚Äôs been going to school ever since. ‚ÄúThe mother was amazed. They thought his lack of energy was from the heart condition, but he basically had been depressed,‚Äù notes Olson. ‚ÄúAnd the best part,‚Äù she adds, ‚Äúis that he tried out for choir, and he made it!‚Äù</p>
<p>Another student attended her class field trip to an aquarium, thanks to her telepresence robot. ‚ÄúThe students were gathered around the robot, making sure their friend was correctly positioned to see all of the same fun things they were seeing,‚Äù says Olson.</p>
<div id="attachment_4362" style="width: 1210px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-4362" src="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="800" srcset="https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction.jpg 1200w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-StudentInteraction-624x416.jpg 624w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Children interacting with a student through a telepresence robot.</p></div>
<p>The homebound students are thus not only getting the benefits of attending classes, they‚Äôre also reconnecting with peers and participating in activities otherwise not available to them. ‚ÄúThe families really appreciate the fact that the children are in school. And they appreciate the social experiences and feeling of belonging,‚Äù notes Olson.</p>
<p>Given the importance of the social aspects, Olson is considering the needs of both the student and his or her classmates. And she admits that, at times, there have been instances of bullying. One boy, referring to a telepresence robot, laughed and said, ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs that? A vacuum cleaner?‚Äù Another put a ‚Äúkick me‚Äù sign on the back of a robot. A homebound student even had ketchup smeared on his robot‚Äôs face screen, though he couldn‚Äôt see it because the screen was below the camera. In this case, after the teacher cleaned the screen, a group of students volunteered to be his ‚Äúposse,‚Äù looking out for him. As Olson explains, ‚Äúbullying is a part of school life,‚Äù so this needs to be addressed during design and implementation. Designating a ‚Äúposse‚Äù of enthusiastic helpers is one possible solution.</p>
<p>Generally, though, Olson says that ‚Äúpeople are really caring about this population. It‚Äôs important to include these children in school, so the other children understand what they‚Äôre dealing with; otherwise, you never see it. You don‚Äôt see a child who is bald because of chemo.‚Äù So she continues to explore how best to design these experiences, both for the homebound students and others, noting that telepresence can open up the world for the homebound while also providing rich experiences for their peers.</p>
<p>Newhart and Olson must also consider certain policy issues, because there‚Äôs now a video connection between the school and home. Olson reports that in some instances, the parent of a homebound student would see something happening in the classroom and then would comment about it on Facebook. One school district plans to address this by teaching the parents of homebound students to be teachers‚Äô aides, instructing them about the importance of privacy in the classroom as well as the need for a designated ‚Äúschool‚Äù area, given that others can now see into the home. As Olson says, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm very excited that people are adopting these just as they are, but there are issues we need to address.‚Äù</p>
<p><b>Analyzing the Costs and Benefits</b></p>
<p>Of course, the focal point is the robot itself, so Olson is recording what features could improve the experience. Some students say they wish the robot had stereo sound, so they could better identify where a voice is coming from in the classroom. Others wish the robot could move its head separate from its body. Most agree that a joystick would be preferable to the current arrow keys, and voice commands would be even better, so students could say, ‚ÄúTake me to the lunchroom.‚Äù Another recommendation is to include a hotspot on the robots.</p>
<div id="attachment_4365" style="width: 2410px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall.jpg"><img class="wp-image-4365 size-full" src="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall.jpg" alt="" width="2400" height="800" srcset="https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall.jpg 2400w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall-300x100.jpg 300w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall-768x256.jpg 768w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall-1024x341.jpg 1024w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-Judy-office-Gloria-hall-624x208.jpg 624w" sizes="(max-width: 2400px) 100vw, 2400px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Judy Olson, testing out a telepresence robot in Donald Bren Hall, stops to chat with Informatics Professor Gloria Mark. (Robert Farmer/UCI)</p></div>
<p>Olson says they‚Äôre working closely with <a href="https://www.doublerobotics.com/">Double Robotics</a>, which built one of the robots they‚Äôre using. ‚ÄúDavid Cann is the CEO there, and he‚Äôs very receptive to what we‚Äôre finding.‚Äù Newhart and Olson are developing a list of desired features, and Olson‚Äôs next goal is to conduct a cost/benefit analysis. ‚ÄúThey can‚Äôt do them all. Some features are very expensive. How much is it worth to turn your head? What is the cost of social interaction?‚Äù She‚Äôs applying for funding to allow Double Robotics to build a prototype with all of the requested features, which would help them determine the cost of development as well as the pricing for consumers ‚Äî currently parents, teachers and school districts.</p>
<p>However, another area that Newhart is exploring is whether insurance companies might one day pay for such robots. She has a pilot grant from the <a href="https://www.nih.gov/">National Institutes of Health</a> and has applied for continued funding to conduct a clinical trial and explore health outcomes. There are also questions about who would be good candidates for telepresence learning. Newhart and Olson will need to explore whether the child needs a certain level of cognitive ability and energy, or a willingness to make friends, and so on.</p>
<div id="attachment_4366" style="width: 635px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-VNewhart.jpg"><img class="wp-image-4366 size-large" src="http://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-VNewhart-683x1024.jpg" alt="" width="625" height="937" srcset="https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-VNewhart-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-VNewhart-200x300.jpg 200w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-VNewhart.jpg 768w, https://www.informatics.uci.edu/wp-content/informatics/uploads/OlsonDec2017-VNewhart-624x936.jpg 624w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Veronica Newhart, Ph.D. candidate in the School of Education, and a telepresence robot. (Steve Zylius/UCI)</p></div>
<p><b>Telepresence Learning at UCI</b></p>
<p>There‚Äôs clearly a lot to learn, but opportunities for observation just moved significantly closer, thanks to Newhart convincing the class of 2016 to use their <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=140ricVvA_o">class gift</a> to buy telepresence robots for UCI. Now, by going through the <a href="https://www.dsc.uci.edu/">Office of Disability Services</a>, homebound UCI students can borrow a robot; a graduate student undergoing medical treatment has already started using one. This provides an on-campus test case. ‚ÄúWe realized that the robot can‚Äôt go between buildings, because somebody could take it,‚Äù says Olson. ‚ÄúThe more we do, the more we find,‚Äù she adds, making it clear that despite her retirement, she has no plans to stop working anytime soon. But perhaps she‚Äôll take time out to enjoy a choir concert featuring a telepresence robot, letting her hear a boy she knows sing his little heart out.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><i>‚Äî Shani Murray</i></p>
